00:52:02.000 --> 00:52:05.620
It would take me literally
hours, in many cases,

00:52:05.620 --> 00:52:07.860
to have to go out to a store
and buy that same thing.

00:52:07.860 --> 00:52:11.240
Anyway, to me, though, the
really interesting thing

00:52:11.240 --> 00:52:14.530
that you're getting at is the
change in social relationships

00:52:14.530 --> 00:52:16.080
and the kind of atomization.

00:52:16.080 --> 00:52:20.030
Because I think
one of the reasons

00:52:20.030 --> 00:52:24.420
people like to do this is that
in many cases it saves time.

00:52:24.420 --> 00:52:27.230
But another really important
reason is that a lot of people

00:52:27.230 --> 00:52:30.730
just don't like dealing
with other people.

00:52:30.730 --> 00:52:33.730
They would rather check
in at a kiosk than deal

00:52:33.730 --> 00:52:35.520
with somebody
behind the counter.

00:52:35.520 --> 00:52:37.630
They would rather
serve their own food

00:52:37.630 --> 00:52:39.370
than deal with a waitress.

00:52:39.370 --> 00:52:42.750
There's something
about this that I

00:52:42.750 --> 00:52:46.580
think is kind of disturbing.

00:52:46.580 --> 00:52:48.330
A lot of people just
don't want to have

00:52:48.330 --> 00:52:50.970
those kind of incidental
social relationships

00:52:50.970 --> 00:52:53.169
that we used to
be forced to have.

00:52:53.169 --> 00:52:55.460
I think there's something
pretty disturbing about that,

00:52:55.460 --> 00:52:59.170
and I think it is changing the
quality of our relationships.

00:52:59.170 --> 00:53:01.290
And one effect that
it might be having

00:53:01.290 --> 00:53:04.990
is that the amount
of social interaction

00:53:04.990 --> 00:53:08.840
that people of different social
classes have with each other

00:53:08.840 --> 00:53:11.370
may be being reduced.

00:53:11.370 --> 00:53:13.950
I'm not sure about this,
but one hypothesis,

00:53:13.950 --> 00:53:16.580
that some of these
changes are basically

00:53:16.580 --> 00:53:19.550
making more of my
interactions be

00:53:19.550 --> 00:53:22.120
with people of my
own social class,

00:53:22.120 --> 00:53:25.000
and not as many with people
of other social classes,

00:53:25.000 --> 00:53:27.910
in particular of
less affluent people.

00:53:27.910 --> 00:53:29.830
And if that's
really true, I think

00:53:29.830 --> 00:53:33.930
that could have profound
effects on our social life.

00:53:33.930 --> 00:53:36.430
CRAIG LAMBERT: Actually, I think
that's a really interesting

00:53:36.430 --> 00:53:36.930
point.

00:53:36.930 --> 00:53:38.890
It's a fascinating point
that I hadn't actually

00:53:38.890 --> 00:53:41.560
thought of in that
clear a way, which

00:53:41.560 --> 00:53:44.150
is that when you're dealing
with a cashier in a supermarket,

00:53:44.150 --> 00:53:46.970
the teller at the bank, you
may be dealing with someone

00:53:46.970 --> 00:53:50.890
of a considerably different
social class than yourself.

00:53:50.890 --> 00:53:57.000
And when we deal with the ATM
or the kiosk checkout instead,

00:53:57.000 --> 00:53:59.620
those interactions
are disappearing.

00:53:59.620 --> 00:54:07.460
We have a world in
which-- we don't always

00:54:07.460 --> 00:54:11.530
understand what we're doing
when we become our own travel

00:54:11.530 --> 00:54:12.030
agents.

00:54:12.030 --> 00:54:14.960
This is a case that
came to my mind.

00:54:14.960 --> 00:54:18.060
People think, well,
I can go onto the web

00:54:18.060 --> 00:54:20.660
and I can buy my own
tickets, book my own travel.

00:54:20.660 --> 00:54:22.180
And you can.

00:54:22.180 --> 00:54:25.440
But there are still
travel agents.

00:54:25.440 --> 00:54:30.600
And they don't use
Expedia or Kayak.

00:54:30.600 --> 00:54:36.560
They have their own system,
which is a proprietary system.

00:54:36.560 --> 00:54:42.180
And they see things in real
time, the seats in airlines,

00:54:42.180 --> 00:54:44.920
and they're able to do things
that we can't do online.

00:54:44.920 --> 00:54:48.170
I did a trip last
winter to the Caribbean.

00:54:48.170 --> 00:54:52.360
And I realized, I could spend a
whole weekend researching this.

00:54:52.360 --> 00:54:55.890
All of the airlines, the
islands, the fares, the hotels,

00:54:55.890 --> 00:54:58.790
the packages-- I could spend
10 hours with no problem

00:54:58.790 --> 00:55:00.220
researching this trip.

00:55:00.220 --> 00:55:02.310
I said, I don't want to do that.

00:55:02.310 --> 00:55:05.060
I paid $75 fee to
a travel agent.

00:55:05.060 --> 00:55:08.790
That was her commission, and
then she set it up for me.

00:55:08.790 --> 00:55:11.060
And I was very glad to do it.

00:55:11.060 --> 00:55:12.550
So, it's not always equivalent.

00:55:12.550 --> 00:55:15.950
We think that us doing the
job of the travel agent

00:55:15.950 --> 00:55:18.290
is the same as the travel
agent doing the job.

00:55:18.290 --> 00:55:20.900
And it isn't always the case.

00:55:20.900 --> 00:55:22.100
Just sort of a footnote.

00:55:22.100 --> 00:55:23.490
MALE SPEAKER: Let's
take one last question.

00:55:23.490 --> 00:55:23.900
CRAIG LAMBERT: OK.

00:55:23.900 --> 00:55:24.774
AUDIENCE: Yes, hello.

00:55:24.774 --> 00:55:25.820
